Install `jazz-napi` as a direct dependency and create one server-only context:

```ts
import { createJazzContext } from "jazz-tools/backend";
import permissions from "./permissions";
import { app } from "./schema";

export const jazz = createJazzContext({
  appId: process.env.JAZZ_APP_ID!,
  app,
  permissions,
  driver: {
    type: "persistent",
    dataPath: process.env.JAZZ_DATA_PATH ?? "./jazz-data",
  },
  serverUrl: process.env.JAZZ_SERVER_URL,
  backendSecret: process.env.BACKEND_SECRET,
  env: process.env.NODE_ENV === "production" ? "prod" : "dev",
  userBranch: "main",
});
```

Keep this singleton for the process lifetime; do not create a context per request. Use a stable, backed-up `dataPath`, and call `await jazz.shutdown()` during process termination. A memory driver is ephemeral and must have an upstream `serverUrl`. Server-connected backend and request-scoped handles require `BACKEND_SECRET`; keep it and `JAZZ_ADMIN_SECRET` in server-only environment variables. The admin secret is for catalogue, permission, migration, and edge administration—not ordinary application access. Await the required durability tier before returning success when an endpoint promises persisted or server-visible writes.

Build the query inside a reactive accessor.

```svelte
<script lang="ts">
  import { QuerySubscription } from "jazz-tools/svelte";

  let projectId = $state<string | undefined>(undefined);
  const tasks = new QuerySubscription(() =>
    projectId ? app.tasks.where({ projectId }) : undefined,
  );
</script>
```

```tsx
import { createSignal } from "solid-js";
import { useAll } from "jazz-tools/solid";

const [projectId, setProjectId] = createSignal<string | undefined>(undefined);
const tasks = useAll(() => {
  const id = projectId();
  return { query: id ? app.tasks.where({ projectId: id }) : undefined };
});
```

Read Svelte results from `tasks.current` and Solid results from `tasks.data`. `undefined` means skipped or not yet delivered; `[]` means loaded with no matches. [Queries](https://jazz.tools/docs/reading/queries)

Use a batch for writes that should appear optimistically together:

```ts
const optimistic = db.batch((batch) => {
  batch.update(app.todos, firstId, { done: true });
  batch.update(app.todos, secondId, { done: true });
});
```

Use a transaction when both writes must remain staged until authority acceptance, then wait on the combined result for global durability:

```ts
const authoritative = db.transaction((tx) => {
  tx.update(app.todos, firstId, { done: true });
  tx.update(app.todos, secondId, { done: true });
});
await authoritative.wait({ tier: "global" });
```

Do not await individual writes inside either callback. [Writing Data](https://jazz.tools/docs/writing/writing-data#transactions-and-batches)

Define an optional self-reference using the required `Id` suffix:

```ts
import { schema as s } from "jazz-tools";

const schema = {
  employees: s.table({
    name: s.string(),
    managerId: s.ref("employees").optional(),
  }),
};

type AppSchema = s.Schema<typeof schema>;
export const app: s.App<AppSchema> = s.defineApp(schema);
```

`managerId` derives the typed `manager` relation. [Defining Tables](https://jazz.tools/docs/schemas/defining-tables)

Use `s.timestamp()` for a `Date`, inline `s.bytes()` for the row-loaded `Uint8Array` fingerprint, and `s.ref("projects")` for the project ID:

```ts
const schema = {
  projects: s.table({
    name: s.string(),
  }),
  events: s.table({
    occurredAt: s.timestamp(),
    fingerprint: s.bytes(),
    projectId: s.ref("projects"),
  }),
};
```

The `projectId` name satisfies Jazz’s reference naming convention. [Column Types](https://jazz.tools/docs/schemas/column-types)

The current official source is [Defining Tables](https://jazz.tools/docs/schemas/defining-tables). I selected it from Jazz’s official [documentation index](https://jazz.tools/llms.txt), where its description explicitly says it covers defining tables and relationships in `schema.ts`; I then verified the page itself.

```ts
import { schema as s } from "jazz-tools";

const schema = {
  projects: s.table({
    name: s.string(),
  }),
  todos: s.table({
    title: s.string(),
    done: s.boolean(),
    projectId: s.ref("projects").optional(),
  }),
};

export const app = s.defineApp(schema);
export type Todo = s.RowOf<typeof app.todos>;
```

Use `s.table()` for tables, column definers such as `s.string()` and `s.boolean()`, and `s.ref()` for typed relationships. Reference columns must end in `Id` or `_id`; arrays of references must end in `Ids` or `_ids`. Validate the result with `pnpm dlx jazz-tools@alpha validate`.

Use the conventional helper-compatible schema:

```ts
const schema = {
  file_parts: s.table({ data: s.bytes() }),
  files: s.table({
    name: s.string().optional(),
    mimeType: s.string(),
    partIds: s.array(s.ref("file_parts")),
    partSizes: s.array(s.int()),
  }),
  uploads: s.table({
    owner_id: s.string(),
    label: s.string(),
    fileId: s.ref("files"),
  }),
};
```

Grant CRUD on `uploads` only when `owner_id === session.user_id`. Grant file reads/deletes through `uploads.fileId`, and part reads/deletes through `files.partIds`. Because helpers create parts and the file before the parent upload exists, inherited insert permission cannot work; either grant narrowly reviewed direct inserts on `files` and `file_parts`, or upload through a trusted backend. Normally grant no updates because file rows are write-once.

Require edge settlement for both the chunks/file metadata and the owning row:

```ts
const file = await db.createFileFromBlob(app, blob, { tier: "edge" });

const upload = await db
  .insert(app.uploads, {
    owner_id: session.user_id,
    label,
    fileId: file.id,
  })
  .wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

Download at the same tier so missing local chunks can be fetched before reconstruction:

```ts
try {
  const blob = await db.loadFileAsBlob(app, upload.fileId, { tier: "edge" });
  showBlob(blob);
} catch (error) {
  if (error instanceof FileNotFoundError) showMissingFile();
  else if (error instanceof IncompleteFileDataError) {
    showIncompleteFile(error.reason); // invalid-file-record, missing-part, or part-size-mismatch
  } else throw error;
}
```

An edge-tier read can fill an incomplete local snapshot, but cannot repair corrupt metadata or a chunk genuinely missing at the edge. If parent insertion fails after file creation, clean up the already-created file and parts.

Load the relationships first, then delete from the leaves upwards while each inherited permission still has its authorising row:

```ts
const upload = await db.one(app.uploads.where({ id: uploadId }), { tier: "edge" });
if (!upload) return;

const file = await db.one(app.files.where({ id: upload.fileId }), { tier: "edge" });
if (file) {
  for (const partId of file.partIds) {
    await db.delete(app.file_parts, partId).wait({ tier: "edge" });
  }
  await db.delete(app.files, file.id).wait({ tier: "edge" });
}

await db.delete(app.uploads, upload.id).wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

The required order is parts → file → upload. Deleting the upload first removes the relationship authorising file deletion; deleting the file before its parts similarly removes their inherited authorisation.

Use two real clients against a fresh in-memory Jazz server. Await edge durability for every insert, poll Bob’s public query, and normalise rows by a stable key before comparing:

```ts
const expected = ["Alpha", "Bravo", "Charlie"];

await Promise.all(
  expected.map((title) =>
    alice.insert(app.todos, { title, done: false }).wait({ tier: "edge" }),
  ),
);

await vi.waitFor(async () => {
  const rows = await bob.all(app.todos, { tier: "edge" });
  const titles = rows.map(({ title }) => title).sort();

  expect(titles).toEqual([...expected].sort());
});
```

Create unique in-memory clients for each test and shut down both clients and the server in teardown. Sorting prevents unspecified query order from making the test flaky.

Use `createPolicyTestApp` with separate Alice and Bob sessions. Assert denied reads as filtered results and denied writes with `expectDenied`:

```ts
const alice = testApp.as({
  user_id: "alice",
  claims: {},
  authMode: "local-first",
});
const bob = testApp.as({
  user_id: "bob",
  claims: {},
  authMode: "local-first",
});

const todo = alice.insert(app.todos, { title: "Alice’s private row" }).value;

await expect(
  bob.all(app.todos.where({ id: todo.id })),
).resolves.toEqual([]);

bob.expectDenied((db) =>
  db.update(app.todos, todo.id, { title: "Bob’s edit" }),
);
bob.expectDenied((db) => db.delete(app.todos, todo.id));

alice.expectAllowed((db) =>
  db.update(app.todos, todo.id, { title: "Alice’s edit" }),
);
```

Initialise the policy test app in `beforeEach` and call `testApp.shutdown()` in `afterEach`. Do not expect read-policy violations to throw.
